    },
    {
      "id": "0f89941f07be221f2fc62b9887e9e860926b1b4c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-06 16:43:06.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2844f612e112522f8ab0ea5753b754fe022b0e3c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 1,
        "name": "Robert Read",
        "email": "robert.read@intel.com",
        "username": "rread",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-03-06 21:00:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nThe core fix looks ok, but there is no reason to negate errno in the CT_ERROR calls.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a47d76f9f99fd0f54dab23edce9da0ea38728a79",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-21 06:25:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Robert,\n\nI understand what you mean.\n\nMost of the time, we pass negative return values to CT_ERROR, but sometimes, we pass positive values. I know negative or positive is esssentailly the same, because of the implementation of llapi_error. However, it feels better to keep these values all negative neatly (or all positive in reverse). For example, what if we need to change the implementation of CT_ERROR or llapi_error in the future?\n\nThanks,\nLi Xi",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a1030e28732371d4a10712b88924879c7ca5d1df",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 1,
        "name": "Robert Read",
        "email": "robert.read@intel.com",
        "username": "rread",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-03-21 15:54:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIn userspace errno is typically (always?) positive though. It is common (though not standard) for functions to return -1 on error, but the actual error code would be a positive value passed in errno.  I suppose we might want to define our custom error codes as negative numbers, but negating errno itself seems wrong and potentially confusing.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e293600c3f1a4c8d30793201b0e3ca77c034114f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-28 23:10:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBiggest concern I have is that we need to closely watch return values on error not to be in the space that's valid non-error values.\n\nSo e.g. the function returning an FD cannot really return -ENODATA because that's a valid (though unlikely) file descriptor. The only indication of error possible is -1 (and errno set appropriately).\nThis also means a lot of current logic that checks fd to be >=0 for to check for validity is technically incorrect.\n\nSo we likely should drop all -errno from the error prints (esp. since there's abs() call inside anyway).\nAs for actual return values, I guess we really need to do something consistent and returning a negative error almost makes sense (but see the caveat that I started with).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4a04469f909e95ec0a799a55e5036ac203a95cd9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-29 00:25:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi Oleg,\n\nRegarding this patch, I should remove all the -errno change in the CT_ERROR calls, right? I'd roll it back right away since you has the same opinion with Robert on this.\n\nThanks!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2f180d3ed7a45e95699823461493b5d84e2585ff",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-31 01:25:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOleg,\n\nHuh? -ENODATA will never be a valid file descriptor. The last thing we want it to encourage is rc == -1 checking since that will be broken when an -errno is returned. Negative ints are not and will not be valid file descriptors on Linux, ever.\n\nReturning -errno of failure is the sanest possible practice here.\n\nWith regard to io offset sizes it's different. There we should be using size_t in, and ssize_t out like the rest of the civilized world. No more int for everything.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e5d17c38db996a96ceee946fd25318bdd9bab18a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
